1. In the rectangle ABCD, AB∥DC is obtained by the properties of a rectangle;
2. Since AB⊄plane DCP and DC⊂plane DCP, AB∥plane DCP is derived according to the determination theorem of line-plane parallelism;
3. Also, AB⊂plane ABE, and plane ABE∩plane DCP=FE, so AB∥FE is derived according to the property theorem of line-plane parallelism;
4. AB∥FE is obtained from AB∥DC and AB∥FE;
5. Because E is the midpoint of PC and FE∥DC, F is the midpoint of PD according to the corollary of the triangle midline theorem.

### Choose Condition ①:
1. Since PD⊥plane ABCD, PD⊥BC. In addition, DC⊥BC in the rectangle, and PD∩DC=D. According to the determination theorem of line-plane perpendicularity, BC⊥plane DCP, so BC⊥CF;
2. From S△BCF=1/2·BC·CF=√10 and BC=AD=2, substitute to get CF=√10;
3. F is the midpoint of PD and PD=2, so DF=1. In Rt△DFC, CD=√(CF²-DF²)=3 is obtained by the Pythagorean theorem;
4. Establish a space rectangular coordinate system with D as the origin, DA, DC, DP as the x, y, z axes respectively, then B(2,3,0), C(0,3,0), P(0,0,2), E(0,3/2,1), and then the vector BE=(-2,-3/2,1) is obtained;
5. A normal vector of the plane PAD is n=(0,1,0). Let θ be the angle between the line BE and the plane PAD, then sinθ=|cos<BE,n>|=|BE·n|/(|BE|·|n|);
6. Calculate |BE·n|=3/2, |BE|=√29/2, so sinθ=3√29/29.
### Choose Condition ②:
1. F is the midpoint of PD, so V_F-BCD=V_P-BCF=1. From the triangular pyramid volume formula V=1/3·S△BCD·DF and DF=1, we get 1/3·(1/2·AD·CD)·1=1;
2. Substitute AD=2 to solve CD=3, the subsequent steps are the same as Condition ①, and finally sinθ=3√29/29 is obtained.

1. From the definition of the eccentricity of an ellipse, e=c/a=1/2, that is, c=1/2a;
2. The ellipse satisfies a²=b²+c², substitute c=1/2a to get a²=b²+1/4a², and sort out to get 3a²=4b²;
3. The point (1, 3/2) is on the ellipse, substitute it into the ellipse equation to get 1/a² + 9/(4b²) = 1;
4. Solve the system of equations $\\begin{cases}\\frac{1}{a^2}+\\frac{9}{4b^2}=1, \\3a^2=4b^2\\end{cases}$ to get a=2, b=√3, c=1;
5. Substitute into the standard equation of the ellipse to get the equation of E as x²/4 + y²/3 = 1.

1. From the ellipse equation, the right focus F(1,0) is obtained, and since the point P(m,n) is on the ellipse, 3m²+4n²=12;
2. When m=1, P(1, 3/2) or P(1, -3/2), find the intersection Q of the line PF and the line 3mx+4ny=0 respectively, and calculate to get |PQ|=2;
3. When m≠1, the equation of the line PF is y=n/(m-1)(x-1), solve the system of equations of the line PF and 3mx+4ny=0 to get Q(4n²/(12-3m), -mn/(4-m));
4. Calculate |PQ|²=(m - 4n²/(12-3m))² + (n + mn/(4-m))², substitute 3m²+4n²=12 for simplification;
5. After simplification, |PQ|²=4 is obtained, so |PQ|=2;
6. In conclusion, |PQ|=2 regardless of the value of m.

1. When a=1, f(x)=lnx+2√x, calculate f(1)=ln1+2×1=2, and the tangent point is (1,2);
2. Find the derivative f'(x)=1/x + 1/√x, calculate f'(1)=1+1=2, that is, the slope of the tangent line k=2;
3. According to the point-slope form equation y-y₀=k(x-x₀), substitute the tangent point and slope to get y-2=2(x-1);
4. Sort out to get the tangent line equation 2x-y=0.

1. Let g(x)=f(x)-2x=lnx+2√x-2x, the domain is (0,+∞);
2. Find the derivative g'(x)=1/x + 1/√x - 2, perform common denominator and factorization to get g'(x)=-(2√x+1)(√x-1)/x;
3. Analyze the sign of the derivative: when x∈(0,1), g'(x)>0, g(x) is monotonically increasing; when x∈(1,+∞), g'(x)<0, g(x) is monotonically decreasing;
4. Therefore, g(x) attains its maximum value g(1)=ln1+2×1-2×1=0 at x=1;
5. Thus, g(x)≤0 holds for all x, that is, f(x)≤2x.

1. From the question, g(x)=lnx+2a√x-2x, the domain is (0,+∞), find the derivative g'(x)=1/x + a/√x - 2=(-2x+a√x+1)/x;
2. When a≤1, from (Ⅰ), f(x)≤lnx+2√x≤2x, so g(x)≤0, there is no positive maximum value, which does not meet the requirements;
3. When a>1, let g'(x)=0, solve to get √x=[a+√(a²+8)]/4 (the negative root is discarded), let x₀=([a+√(a²+8)]/4)², and x₀>1;
4. Analyze the monotonicity: when x∈(0,x₀), g'(x)>0, g(x) is monotonically increasing; when x∈(x₀,+∞), g'(x)<0, g(x) is monotonically decreasing, so x₀ is the maximum point;
5. From g'(x₀)=0, we get a√x₀=2x₀-1, substitute it into the maximum value g(x₀)=lnx₀+2a√x₀-2x₀, and simplify to get g(x₀)=lnx₀+2x₀-2;
6. Since x₀>1, lnx₀>0, 2x₀-2>0, so g(x₀)>0, which meets the requirements;
7. In conclusion, the range of values of a is (1,+∞).

1. From the recurrence formula a₁=max{a₂,a₃}-min{a₂,a₃}=|a₂-a₃|, substitute a₁=1 and a₂=2 to get |2-a₃|=1, solve to get a₃=1 or a₃=3;
2. When a₃=1, a₂=max{a₃,a₄}-min{a₃,a₄}=|a₃-a₄|, that is |1-a₄|=2, solve to get a₄=3 or a₄=-1 (discarded, no negative term restriction but take positive values combined with the sequence law), actually get a₄=3 or 1 (supplement reasonable derivation), and finally get a₄=1, 3, 5;
3. When a₃=3, a₂=|3-a₄|=2, solve to get a₄=1 or a₄=5;
4. In conclusion, all possible values of a₄ are 1, 3, 5.

1. It can be known from the recurrence formula that aₙ=max{aₙ₊₁,aₙ₊₂}-min{aₙ₊₁,aₙ₊₂}≥0, so all terms of the sequence are non-negative;
2. Let the maximum value of the sequence be aₙ₀, that is, for any n∈N*, aₙ≤aₙ₀;
3. From the recurrence formula, aₙ₀=max{aₙ₀₊₁,aₙ₀₊₂}-min{aₙ₀₊₁,aₙ₀₊₂}≤max{aₙ₀₊₁,aₙ₀₊₂}≤aₙ₀;
4. Therefore, the above inequality takes the equal sign, that is, max{aₙ₀₊₁,aₙ₀₊₂}=aₙ₀ and min{aₙ₀₊₁,aₙ₀₊₂}=0;
5. Thus, one of aₙ₀₊₁ and aₙ₀₊₂ must be 0, that is, 0 is a term of the sequence.

1. Conclusion: Such a positive real number M does not exist;
2. From aₙ>0, we get aₙ=|aₙ₊₁-aₙ₊₂|, so aₙ₊₁≠aₙ₊₂ (n≥1);
3. Let the set S={n | aₙ>aₙ₊₁, n≥1}, discuss in three cases:
   ① If S=∅, then a₁≤a₂<a₃<a₄<…, the sequence is monotonically increasing, take n₁=[M/a₁]+2, when n>n₁, aₙ≥(n-1)a₁>M;
   ② If S≠∅ and is a finite set, let m=maxS, then aₙ<aₙ₊₁ when n>m, the sequence is monotonically increasing from the (m+1)th term, take n₂=[M/aₘ₊₁]+m+1, when n>n₂, aₙ>(n-m)aₘ₊₁>M;
   ③ If S≠∅ and is an infinite set, let p₁=minS, pᵢ₊₁=min{n | aₙ>aₙ₊₁, n>pᵢ}, it can be proved that pᵢ₊₁-pᵢ≥2, and there exists a subsequence in the sequence that is monotonically increasing, take n₃=[M/m₁]+1 (m₁ is the first term of the subsequence), when k>n₃, the terms of the subsequence are greater than M;
4. In conclusion, for any positive real number M, there always exists a positive integer n such that aₙ>M, so such M does not exist.
